<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-79-0794 </DOCNO><TEXT>The Sizewell-B Public Inquiry was long and expensive. The benefits ofthe Inquiry are listed. However, five aspects were not so good. Thesewere the linkages between party politics, government policies and thepressurized water reactor application, confusion over the relationshipbetween the official licensing procedures and the Inquiry treatment ofsafety, the uncertainties over forecasting economic trends, underfundingof objecting groups, and also the scope became very wide-ranging. Recommendationsare made to make the future inquiries about PWRs shorter and less costly.However, the Public Inquiry is still seen as the best public platformfor reasoned analysis. (U.K.).</TEXT></DOC>